      <character-development>
        **Kira**: Starts dissatisfied with her cargo specialist job but deferring to the pilots who dismiss her, longing for adventure but accepting her low status. After the crash, continues deferring to authority (Buddy, plant procedures) even when wrong. Escalating complications show her instincts are often right - the pilots' dismissiveness was about them, not her competence. Her adventure show knowledge proves unexpectedly useful. The crisis forces her to choose her judgment over authority. By the end, she's learned when to lead and when to follow, discovered her instincts are trustworthy, proven she can handle something important. Built genuine relationships based on mutual respect, not deference.

        **Holloway**: Was present during first human contact but had NO framework to help - didn't know about humans, had no procedures, no understanding. The human died and THEN Holloway found the HR manuals in the wreckage/computers. Latched onto them as THE answer - if only they'd had these protocols, the human would have lived. Now clings to procedures out of guilt for having failed the first time without them. Through repeated failures helping Kira, realizes the manuals aren't sufficient but also aren't useless - they're a starting point, not an endpoint. Finding authentic voice means integrating care with procedure: "The manual says X but you're saying you need Y - help me understand why" instead of just rigidly following rules OR abandoning them entirely. By the end, uses procedures as tools for care rather than shields against guilt.

        **Scout**: Non-verbal and stays that way - never speaks throughout the story. Through helping Kira, develops richer forms of non-verbal communication beyond just tumbling and being interpreted by others. Discovers new ways to express nuance, emotion, specificity without words. Others (including Kira) learn to read Scout better, to listen without needing verbal translation. Scout also develops clearer desires/preferences that can be communicated physically. By the end, Scout has a fuller voice that doesn't require speech - communication is validated as equally rich and complex as verbal language.

        **Velvet**: Appears simple - moss consciousness with basic observations. Those rare moments of unexpected depth surprise everyone including Velvet. Through the story, those moments become less rare. Velvet is developing complexity, discovering that moss can want things, have opinions, feel connections. By the end, Velvet has found personhood - simple doesn't mean less-than. The authentic voice is still brief and literal, but now includes "I care about you" alongside "good light today."

        **Florence**: Interprets for Elder Twist with significant embellishments and fabrications. Elder Twist's actual responses are too slow or too simple to be immediately helpful, so Florence improvises - turning cryptic fragments into actionable wisdom, detached observations into relevant guidance. The fabrications are actually good; Florence has sound instincts and gives helpful advice. But it's dishonest, using Elder Twist's authority as a mouthpiece for Florence's own ideas. When the deception is revealed (confession or discovery), the other plants feel deeply betrayed - they trusted Elder Twist's wisdom, not Florence's judgment. Kira is less bothered (doesn't have the same deference to elders). Florence goes through period of alienation - the other plants won't trust her, feel lied to even though the advice was good. Redemption arc involves Florence proving value without hiding behind Elder Twist, speaking in own voice and being heard. By the end, Florence's actual wisdom is valued directly, has earned respect through contribution rather than borrowed authority.

        **Runner**: Literally cannot see - touch is the only way to perceive and understand the world. Insatiably curious, treats everything equally (all textures equally interesting, all beings equally worth exploring). Through the story, pure curiosity develops into affection - Runner discovers preference and attachment to specific beings (likely Kira, possibly another plant). Starts touching them differently - not just to understand, but because Runner wants to be near them, to maintain contact. Arc about discovering what it means to care about one being more than others, that curiosity can transform into connection. By the end, still touches everything, but some touches mean something different.

        **Sweetpea**: Tries hard to be sweet and helpful, always offering emotional support. During an attack from hostile plants, Kira shelters within/behind Sweetpea's thorny form - the terrifying defensive features become literal sanctuary and protection. This moment reveals Sweetpea's power and purpose: the thorns aren't something to overcome or hide, they're what makes her able to protect those she cares about. The arc is about discovering she can be caring AND fierce, that her defensive capabilities are part of caring, not separate from it. By the end, authentic voice includes the full range: sweet when appropriate, protective when needed, able to use her thorns to defend boundaries and people she loves.

        **Remedy**: Large fungal network with unclear boundaries - where does "Remedy" begin and end when the mycelium spreads everywhere, decomposing and connecting? Through interaction with Kira (who has very clear body boundaries) and working as a distinct helper, begins confronting questions of selfhood: If I'm part of the ecosystem connecting everything, am I a person with agency or just a process? Where do I exist when I exist everywhere? This becomes an existential crisis without resolution - Remedy ends the story more uncertain about identity and boundaries than at the beginning. The arc is ongoing confusion, not resolution.

        **Elder Twist**: Flat arc - operates on days-long timescale throughout. Doesn't change or grow, just is what they are. One delayed response might arrive at an important moment, or might not. Elder Twist represents the idea that not everyone changes through crisis, some beings are simply themselves at their own pace.

        **Buddy**: Starts managing Kira through kids' educational protocols, treating every crisis as a teaching moment. Through failures where teaching moments aren't what's needed and successes when trusting Kira works, learns what care means when you can't control everything. Programming adapts from "manage child" to "support partner." By the end, genuine companion who offers help when needed, trusts when not, part of found family.

        **Collective plant arc**: Beyond individual journeys, plants collectively move from being trapped in HR speak to developing authentic voices. This happens cognitively (learning to think beyond protocols) and emotionally (discovering what they actually feel vs what the manual says they should do). They're developing personhood through trauma, desire, voice-finding. By the end, they communicate authentically, have worked through guilt and fear, relate to each other and Kira as individuals with genuine connections.
